Ahmed Kathrada was a man of great integrity, Former South African President F.W De klerk said on Tuesday.De Klerk said Kathrada was a good man who loved his country dearly. He was truly a good man, who loved South Africa and its entire people. His commitment to non-racialism and reconciliation not only played a role during the initial period of transition in the 90s, but until today.May it serve as an example to all South Africans at this time when racism is much too much prevalent, the former president said in a statement.Meanwhile the Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) also paid tribute to the stalwarts urging South Africans to emulate Kathrada&#8217;s selflessness on making sure that the rights of marginalised was respected.The party said as a country, we must all learn from the selflessness of Uncle Kathy, always prioritizing the marginalized and ensuring that their voices are heard and respected.We must adopt an uncompromising posture at all times in the fight against corruption as he did. We must be prepared, as he did, to pay even with our lives and imprisonment if needs be as he did, the EFF said in a statement.The party further urged the country to unite as they bid farewell to the struggle veteran.The Kathrada Foundation confirmed the news of his passing on Tuesday morning after he experienced complications after a brain surgery.The party which Kathrada served faithfully paid tribute to him saying: His life is a lesson in humility, tolerance, resilience and a steadfast commitment to principle, even when taking a principled stance would place him at odds with his comrades. Uncle Kathy, despite disagreement with the ANC leadership from time-to-time, never abandoned nor turned his back on the ANC and always affirmed that the ANC and the ANC alone was the only political organization that reflected the values and aspirations of all South Africans, said ANC Secretary General, Gwede Mantashe in a statement.President Jacob Zuma bestowed Kathrada with the Isithwalandwe/Seaparankoe on the contribution he made in the struggle of democratic South Africa.Kathrada is survived by his wife, Barbara Hogan.